Duodecimo.

29
00:01:54,855 --> 00:01:55,456
Chapter 3.

30
00:01:55,636 --> 00:01:56,277
Mealy Mouth.

31
00:01:56,837 --> 00:01:57,298
Porpoise.

32
00:01:57,759 --> 00:02:03,086
The largest kind of porpoise, and only found in the Pacific, so far as it is known.

33
00:02:03,306 --> 00:02:16,283
The only English name by which he has hitherto been designated is that of the fisher's right whale porpoise, from the circumstance that he is chiefly found in the vicinity of that folio.

34
00:02:16,263 --> 00:02:23,932
In shape, he differs in some degree from the Husa porpoise, being of a less rotund and jolly girth, indeed.

35
00:02:24,473 --> 00:02:27,477
He is of quite a neat and gentlemanlike figure.

36
00:02:28,118 --> 00:02:31,662
He has no fins on his back, most other porpoises have.

37
00:02:32,122 --> 00:02:36,668
He has a lovely tail, and sentimental Indian eyes of a hazel hue.

38
00:02:36,648 --> 00:02:38,873
But his mealy mouth spoils all.

39
00:02:38,953 --> 00:02:56,310
Though his entire back down to his side fins as of a deep sable, yet a boundary line, distinct as the mark in a ship's hull, called the bright waist, that line streaks him from stem to stern, with two separate colors, black above and white below.

40
00:02:56,290 --> 00:03:05,580
The white comprises part of his head and the whole of his mouth, which makes him look as if he had just escaped from a felonious visit to a meal-bag.

41
00:03:06,401 --> 00:03:08,724
A most mean and mealy aspect.

42
00:03:09,485 --> 00:03:12,848
His oil is much like that of the common porpoise.

43
00:03:12,868 --> 00:03:19,936
Beyond the duodecimo this system does not proceed inasmuch as the porpoise is the smallest of the whales.

44
